Launch Goals And Security Requirements

Critical Before Publish

- [x] Build real wallet authentication on the server.
- [x] Add nonce generation and signature verification for wallet login.
- [x] Issue and validate an HttpOnly session cookie after successful wallet auth.
- [x] Add logout and session invalidation.
- [x] Create a server helper for authenticated user lookup so routes stop trusting client identity.

- [x] Remove authorization based on userId, clientId, and freelancerId coming from query params or request bodies.
- [x] Refactor escrow management, detail, sync, and summary routes to derive identity from the server session.
- [x] Refactor frontend API calls so they stop sending identity as an authorization mechanism.

- [x] Require proof of wallet ownership before creating a user record.
- [x] Prevent user creation for arbitrary wallet addresses submitted by the client.

- [x] Verify escrow creation against on-chain data before persisting database state.
- [x] Verify tx receipt, contract address, actor wallet, and expected event logs on create.
- [x] Verify escrow sync actions against the authenticated actor and matching on-chain receipt data.
- [x] Reject client-supplied escrow state when it does not match blockchain facts.

- [ ] Lock down public data exposure.
- [ ] Remove or protect public GET endpoints that list users or escrows.
- [ ] Review username and wallet lookup endpoints for account enumeration risk.

- [ ] Add security headers in Next.js config.
- [ ] Add CSP.
- [ ] Add X-Content-Type-Options.
- [ ] Add Referrer-Policy.
- [ ] Add clickjacking protection via frame-ancestors or equivalent.
- [ ] Add a restrictive Permissions-Policy.

- [ ] Enforce HTTPS-only production deployment.
- [ ] Ensure NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL uses the real HTTPS origin in production.
- [ ] Review all NEXT_PUBLIC_* variables and confirm no secrets are exposed.

- [ ] Add rate limiting and abuse protection.
- [ ] Rate-limit user creation.
- [ ] Rate-limit wallet and username lookup endpoints.
- [ ] Rate-limit message submission.
- [ ] Add bot protection to public contact flows.

- [ ] Tighten validation rules.
- [ ] Validate escrow amount format and bounds.
- [ ] Validate deadline format and allowed ranges.
- [ ] Enforce allowed escrow state transitions.
- [ ] Add max length limits for contact messages and other free-text fields.

- [ ] Add security-focused tests.
- [ ] Test forged userId and unauthorized escrow access.
- [ ] Test fake wallet/user creation attempts.
- [x] Test invalid tx hashes and mismatched escrow sync requests.
- [ ] Test public endpoint access rules.

Implementation Order

1. Wallet auth and session foundation.
2. Route authorization refactor to session-derived identity.
3. Escrow create/sync verification against blockchain data.
4. Public surface reduction for user and escrow endpoints.
5. Security headers, HTTPS, and env hardening.
6. Rate limiting and abuse controls.
7. Validation hardening and security tests.

Publish Gate

- [x] Users must prove wallet ownership before a server session exists.
- [ ] No sensitive route may trust caller identity from request body or query string.
- [x] Escrow persistence and sync must be verified against blockchain data.
- [ ] Public list endpoints must be removed or explicitly protected.
- [ ] Security headers, HTTPS, and rate limiting must be in place.
- [ ] Security tests must cover unauthorized access and forged requests.
